            <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-surface-100 mb-1">Line Graph: Internet Usage in Three Countries (2000–2020)</h2>
            <p class="text-xs text-surface-500 mb-4">Prompt: The graph below shows the percentage of internet users in three countries between 2000 and 2020. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.</p>
            <div class="bg-surface-900 rounded-xl p-5 border border-surface-700 text-surface-300 leading-relaxed text-sm space-y-3">
                <p>The line graph illustrates the proportion of people who used the internet in Australia, Brazil and China over a twenty-year period from 2000 to 2020.</p>
                <p>Overall, internet usage increased significantly in all three countries during this period. Australia had the highest usage throughout, while China showed the most dramatic growth.</p>
                <p>In 2000, Australia had approximately 45% of its population online, which steadily climbed to around 87% by 2020. Brazil started much lower at roughly 5%, but grew consistently, reaching approximately 70% by the end of the period. China began with the lowest figure of under 2% in 2000, yet experienced the steepest rise, eventually surpassing Brazil and reaching about 73% in 2020.</p>
                <p>The most notable change occurred in China between 2005 and 2015, when usage increased by nearly 40 percentage points. By contrast, Australia's growth slowed after 2010, suggesting that the market was approaching saturation. Brazil maintained a steady, gradual increase throughout the entire period without any significant acceleration.</p>
