            <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-surface-100 mb-1">Line Graph: Internet Usage in Three Countries (2000–2020)</h2>
            <p class="text-xs text-surface-500 mb-4">Same prompt as above — notice the superior precision, cohesion, and vocabulary range.</p>
            <div class="bg-surface-900 rounded-xl p-5 border border-surface-700 text-surface-300 leading-relaxed text-sm space-y-3">
                <p>The line graph depicts changes in the percentage of internet users across three nations — Australia, Brazil, and China — over the two decades from 2000 to 2020.</p>
                <p>At a glance, internet adoption grew substantially in every country, albeit at markedly different rates and from very different starting points. Australia maintained its position as the most digitally connected of the three throughout the period, while China's extraordinary acceleration ultimately allowed it to overtake Brazil by around 2018.</p>
                <p>In 2000, Australia led with approximately 45% penetration, rising at a relatively moderate pace to peak at around 87% in 2020 — a near doubling over twenty years. Brazil's trajectory was similarly consistent, climbing from a modest 5% to roughly 70%, though it never closed the gap with Australia.</p>
                <p>China's growth was by far the most striking. Starting at a negligible 2% in 2000, the country underwent exponential expansion, particularly between 2005 and 2015 when usage surged by nearly 45 percentage points. This surge likely reflects massive infrastructure investment and rapid urbanisation. By 2020, China's rate of approximately 73% had edged past Brazil, making it the second most connected country in the dataset.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-3 text-xs text-surface-500">
