            <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-surface-100 mb-1">Should Technology Replace Teachers in Schools?</h2>
            <p class="text-xs text-surface-500 mb-4">Same prompt as above — observe the nuanced argument, varied sentence structures, and precise lexical choices.</p>
            <div class="bg-surface-900 rounded-xl p-5 border border-surface-700 text-surface-300 leading-relaxed text-sm space-y-3">
                <p>The proposition that technology might render teachers obsolete reflects the rapid acceleration of artificial intelligence and digital learning platforms. While I fully concede that technology has transformed the educational landscape, I am firmly of the view that it will never supplant human teachers — and that pursuing such a goal would be fundamentally misguided.</p>
                <p>Proponents of this idea point to the considerable advantages of adaptive learning software. Platforms powered by AI can diagnose a student's precise gaps in knowledge, tailor exercises accordingly, and provide instant, consistent feedback — capabilities that a teacher managing thirty students cannot easily replicate. In regions where qualified educators are scarce, such technology has undeniably democratised access to quality instruction.</p>
                <p>Nevertheless, these capabilities address only the informational dimension of education. Teaching, at its finest, is a deeply relational act. A perceptive teacher recognises when a student's disengagement stems not from incomprehension but from anxiety, grief, or domestic instability. They cultivate intellectual curiosity by modelling passionate inquiry, challenging comfortable assumptions, and nurturing resilience in the face of failure. No machine learning model, however sophisticated, can replicate this holistic mentorship.</p>
                <p>Furthermore, education serves a socialising function that extends well beyond the transmission of knowledge. Schools are environments where children learn negotiation, empathy, and collaborative problem-solving through sustained human interaction. Virtual instruction, even at its most polished, cannot adequately substitute for this irreplaceable dimension of development.</p>
                <p>In short, technology is most valuable as an instrument in the hands of skilled educators, not as their replacement. The future of education lies in a thoughtful partnership between human ingenuity and technological capability — one that preserves the irreducibly human heart of teaching.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-3 text-xs text-surface-500">
