        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-surface-200">What separates a Band 7 from a Band 9 IELTS essay?</h2>
        <p>IELTS examiners assess writing on four criteria: Task Achievement (or Task Response for Task 2), Coherence and Cohesion, Lexical Resource, and Grammatical Range and Accuracy — each weighted equally. A Band 7 response typically presents a clear position with well-developed ideas and a good range of vocabulary, but may show some imprecision or repetition. A Band 9 response demonstrates full task achievement with a fully extended and well-supported argument, uses a wide range of sophisticated vocabulary with natural precision, and shows complete command of grammar with only negligible errors.</p>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-surface-200 mt-6">How do I improve my IELTS writing score?</h2>
        <p>The most reliable way to improve is to write regularly and get detailed AI feedback on each submission. Focus on building a repertoire of academic collocations, practise signposting your argument clearly, and study band 9 model answers to internalise the level of precision expected. Aim to write at least 150 words for Task 1 and 250 words for Task 2.</p>
